stylometry: you would use aggregate planning when trying to find out how much inventory you should produce in a given period to maximise your profits, and minimise your fixed cost of storing the inventory, so that you do not have excess inventory and wasted money, but also so you meet demand and satisfy customers so that you dont go out of business. aggregate planning allows you to consider different variables with running your business so that you can plan accordingly and utilize the components of a business so you make the most money and become a success. You need to consider fixed costs, variable costs, how many units to produce, how to meet customer demands, and how many to keep in inventory. If you produce too much to make sure your demands are met, you have to spend more on inventory costs. If you produce too little you might not satisfy demands and eventually go out of business.
